      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(cli): retry logs.tail after journal fallback in logs follow",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nFixes `openclaw logs --follow` getting stuck on Linux systemd journal fallback after a transient local Gateway RPC outage or Gateway restart.\n\nWhen implicit local `logs.tail` fails in follow mode, the CLI can use the active systemd journal as a bridge. However, after a journal payload was emitted, the follow loop permanently latched journal mode and stopped probing `logs.tail`. That meant log presentation could remain journal/console-style until the CLI was restarted, even after Gateway RPC recovered.\n\nThis keeps journal fallback temporary:\n- preserve the journal cursor so repeated fallback reads do not duplicate journal output;\n- do not permanently force journal mode after a journal fallback payload;\n- retry `logs.tail` on the next follow iteration so recovered RPC switches back to normal Gateway log formatting/source.\n\n## Related\n\n- Related issue: #66841\n- Follow-up to #85380, which added active systemd journal fallback to avoid stale configured-file following.\n\n## Behavior\n\n- Implicit local `openclaw logs --follow`:\n  - transient RPC failure can emit active systemd journal fallback logs;\n  - later successful `logs.tail` resumes normal RPC/file log output;\n  - stale configured-file fallback is still not used for follow mode outages.\n- Explicit `--url` behavior is unchanged.\n\n\n## Reviewer / AI review map\n\n- **Scope:** `openclaw logs --follow` source-selection state only; this does not change explicit `--url` behavior or the active systemd journal bridge itself.\n- **Before:** one journal fallback payload latched follow mode into journal output and stopped retrying local Gateway `logs.tail`.\n- **After:** journal fallback can bridge a transient outage, but the next follow iteration retries `logs.tail`; when RPC recovers, output returns to normal Gateway log formatting/source.\n- **Non-overlap:** this is a CLI follow-loop state fix, not a Gateway config/runtime lifecycle change and not a general logging backend rewrite.\n- **Review focus:** cursor preservation across repeated fallback reads, removal of the persistent journal latch, and resuming the Gateway cursor after recovered `logs.tail`.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior addressed:** After this patch, implicit local `openclaw logs --follow` retries `logs.tail` after a temporary systemd-journal fallback. Repeated fallback reads preserve the journal cursor, and a later successful `logs.tail` returns the follow session to normal Gateway RPC/file log output instead of staying journal-latched.\n- **Real setup tested:** Disposable non-production OpenClaw checkout at PR head `aea512eec0ff0f6ecd096d05c0941041c05956c7`, using a synthetic profile/home, a loopback fake Gateway WebSocket that implements the real Gateway protocol handshake and `logs.tail` method, and fake `systemctl`/`journalctl` binaries at the OS boundary. No production Gateway, live runtime state, live config, or real system service was used.\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:** Built the CLI startup bundle, started the fake Gateway on loopback, then ran the actual CLI follow command against the disposable profile with synthetic systemd tools first in `PATH`:\n\n  ```bash\n  OPENCLAW_GATEWAY_PORT=19081   HOME=<synthetic-home>   OPENCLAW_STATE_DIR=<synthetic-home>/.openclaw   OPENCLAW_PROFILE=proof   OPENCLAW_SYSTEMD_UNIT=openclaw-proof-gateway   PATH=<synthetic-bin>:<proof-bin>:$PATH   timeout 8s node openclaw.mjs logs --follow --plain --interval 50 --timeout 700\n  ```\n\n  The timeout wrapper only bounded the long-running follow command; the evidence below was emitted before timeout.\n- **Evidence after fix:** The fake Gateway log recorded two initial failed `logs.tail` calls, then recovered Gateway RPC calls including cursor resume:\n\n  ```text\n  logs.tail call #1 -> terminate-for-fallback\n  logs.tail call #2 -> terminate-for-fallback\n  logs.tail call #3 -> recovered line cursor=10\n  logs.tail call #4 -> cursor=10, recovered line cursor=20\n  ```\n\n  The CLI output showed journal fallback lines followed by recovered Gateway RPC/file log lines:\n\n  ```text\n  Log source: journalctl --user --boot --user-unit=openclaw-proof-gateway.service _PID=4242\n  Service PID: 4242\n  Service Unit: openclaw-proof-gateway.service\n  first journal bridge line\n  second journal bridge line\n  2026-06-03T07:45:00.000+00:00 info gateway rpc recovered line cursor=10\n  2026-06-03T07:45:00.000+00:00 info gateway rpc recovered line cursor=20\n  ```\n\n  The fake `journalctl` invocation log also showed cursor-preserving follow reads:\n\n  ```text\n  journalctl ... --show-cursor -n 200\n  journalctl ... --show-cursor --after-cursor=s=abc\n  journalctl ... --show-cursor --after-cursor=s=def\n  ```\n- **Observed result after fix:** The actual CLI process first fell back to the synthetic systemd journal when local `logs.tail` failed, kept retrying Gateway RPC instead of latching onto journal mode, then resumed Gateway log output after the fake Gateway recovered. The recovered RPC call used the Gateway cursor from the prior successful response (`cursor=10`), while journal fallback calls used `--after-cursor`, confirming both cursor paths advance independently.\n- **What was not tested:** No production Gateway, no live OpenClaw runtime state, no live config, and no real systemd journal/service. The proof uses a disposable checkout plus synthetic loopback Gateway/systemd boundary so the CLI/runtime path is real while the external OS/Gateway boundary is controlled and public-safe.\n",
